[normal]1.This short paper is written by Professor Anthony Trewavas FRS, FRSE, Academia Europea
[normal]. It
[normal] is in response to a request from the Science and Technology committee for information on why the public seem disinclined to go along with its policy on climate change. That assumes its policy is correct, I see a need to be more circumspect. 
[normal]In summary, the following are outlined.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. 
[normal]Unless otherwise stated
[normal],
[normal] the 
[normal]climate 
[normal]evidence to which I refer is to be found on http://climatedata.info and its various subsections on proxies, ice cores, etc.
[normal] This site provides a scientifically
[normal]-
[normal]balanced introduction to climate data.
[normal]The Difference between Projection and Prediction
[normal]3. 
[normal]That there are problems with 
[normal]the 
[normal]public perception of climate change is not surprising and results from the common confusion between pr
[normal]edictions 
[normal]and pr
[normal]ojections.
[normal]  
[normal]A prediction is a defined future; 
[normal]instead, 
[normal]a projection 
[normal]is 
[normal]what might happen
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]It is the difference between 
[normal]certainty and 
[normal]possibility. 
[normal]U
[normal]npredictable events, large volcanic eruptions, asteroids can destroy all attempts at pr
[normal]ediction 
[normal]as can changes in technology.  
[normal]4. 
[normal]Hydraulic fracturing 
[normal]is just one 
[normal]instance; its introduction 
[normal]has 
[normal]made nonsense of many predictions
[normal] of fossil fuel 
[normal]limit
[normal]ations of natural 
[normal]gas resources and 
[normal]also 
[normal]inadvertently reduced USA emissions
[normal]*
[normal]. 
[normal]There will be other technologi
[normal]cal advances
[normal]; we are a highly creative species.
[normal]*
[normal][
[normal]A
[normal]ny scrutiny of the US governments EIA (environmental information administration) would have indicated several centuries worth of technically recoverable reserves of coal, oil or gas].
[normal] 
[normal]5. 
[normal]Climate models can only provide projections, they are not predictions. Confusion between these different words has led to many 
[normal]climat
[normal]e 
[normal]models 
[normal]being presented 
[normal]by government
[normal], NGO’s 
[normal]and some scientists
[normal] 
[normal]as predictions
[normal].
[normal] No doubt those scientists
[normal],
[normal] who did so
[normal],
[normal] were well meaning
[normal]. They admitted sometimes to exaggerating effects to convince the public. But 
[normal]t
[normal]he 
[normal]role 
[normal]of science is to provide unbiased
[normal],
[normal] balanced assessments
[normal].
[normal] If the public are told that climate science predicts continual warming then several 
[normal]very 
[normal]cold winters, lead
[normal]s
[normal] to rejection of the 
[normal]claim
[normal].  
[normal]The complexity of climate 
[normal]render
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]predictions 
[normal]impractica
[normal]b
[normal]l
[normal]e
[normal] 
[normal]and there is 
[normal]need for honesty and transparency about the uncertainties of climate change.
[normal] What was omitted was that climate models 
[normal]at best 
[normal]only offer probabilities
[normal], something it was felt the public would not understand.  
[normal]The essence of science is scepticism.  
[normal]6. 
[normal]Sceptical assessments form the basis of scientific progress. 
[normal]Models are only as good as the information put into them. Questioning climate models is an essential part of progress on understanding.
[normal]7. 
[normal]Those who produced climate models should have been those most vigorous in attacking their own hypotheses and making others aware of their limitations. That is how scientific knowledge expands. Instead as the unfortunate case at the University of East Anglia showed, this group were acting as cheerleaders of their own modelling even to the extent of attempting to d
[normal]amage 
[normal]the credibility of those that questioned what they had published. 
[normal]8. 
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he term Denier or Denialist 
[normal]to describe sceptics 
[normal]is indicative of the closed mind and a term of abuse for the scientific process.  It 
[normal]is 
[normal]reminiscent of Galileo’s problem with the inquisition in the 16
[normal]th
[normal] century and politicians of all kinds should have slapped the term down.  
[normal]9. 
[normal]The last IPCC in 2007
[normal] indicated 
[normal]that there were some 20 or so different models
[normal], projecting estimates anywhere from 1.5 to 6
[normal]◦
[normal] C for 
[normal]either 
[normal]2100
[normal] or a doubling of CO
[normal]2 
[normal]levels
[normal]. T
[normal]hat in itself should have
[normal] negated 
[normal]the notion of climate models as predictions
[normal]. It 
[normal]indicate
[normal]s
[normal] climatological uncertainty
[normal].  The
[normal] variety results from different 
[normal]basic 
[normal]assumptions 
[normal]but given there is only one future, 
[normal]only one
[normal] model 
[normal] or none can actually 
[normal]prove 
[normal]right.
[normal] 
[normal]Can climate models be tested or refuted.
[normal]10. 
[normal]Karl Popper laid down some simple criteria of a scientific enterprise. What is proposed must be capable of being tested or refuted.  
[normal]Whereas normal science is experimental and conforms readily with Popper’s description of easy refutation, climatology is reduced to modelling only and 
[normal]thus suffers inevitable uncertainties
[normal] 
[normal]because knowledge is incomplete
[normal]. 
[normal]The extent of ignorance is unknown.
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he only way 
[normal]a climate model 
[normal]can be refuted is to compare the projections over suitably long periods of time (15-20 years)  with actual climate observations.  
[normal]If policy is based on models
[normal],
[normal] as is the case
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]there is a large inherent risk that after 20 years the policy will have been seen to be wrong because the model was inaccurate
[normal].
[normal] Is this not now 
[normal]beginning to be 
[normal]the case?
[normal]11. 
[normal]All the models proposed in the late 90’s and early noughties have so far proved poor predictors of climate temperature variation and I refer to the apparent stasis in temperature from 1998 onwards. 
[normal]A similar period 
[normal]of
[normal] stasis occurred in the 1940’s and in both cases atmospheric CO
[normal]2
[normal] continued to climb. 
[normal]If this coming year continues
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]as the previous 12-14
[normal] years
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]then the 95% 
[normal]confidence level 
[normal]around the current common mean 
[normal]projected 
[normal]climate temperature
[normal],
[normal] will have been breached
[normal] (
[normal]E. 
[normal]Hawkins. 
[normal]www.climate-lab-book.ac.uk/2013/updated-comparison-of-simulations-and-observations
[normal])
[normal].  
[normal][A breach of the 95% confidence level  indicates a probability of less than 1 in 20 and is usually used in all areas of statistics to indicate 
[normal]high significance
[normal]].
[normal]When politicians were urged to act by some scientists, none of the climate models generated at this time included a period of stasis. 
[normal]All 
[normal]should have been more circumspect.
[normal]12. 
[normal]The apparent stasis indicates that there are aspects to the climate which modellers have not taken into account
[normal] because they are not un
[normal]d
[normal]erstood
[normal]. N
[normal]atural variation 
[normal]is 
[normal]one 
[normal]ascribed reason 
[normal]and 
[normal]something
[normal] 
[normal]studiously ignored 
[normal]20 years ago 
[normal]when mankind was blamed for any change of climate.  I know of no unambiguous way in which natural variation, whatever it is, can ever be distinguished from mankind’s contribution.  Even if the climate temperature had 
[normal]varied as models indicated 
[normal]for 
[normal]a decade or more 
[normal]that does not indicate it is correct
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Correlations are not proof. 
[normal]13. 
[normal]The climate temperature can do one of three things; go up, down or stay the same. Given the error
[normal]s
[normal] in modelling it seems to me that modellers have a 1 in 3 chance of being approximately right. If the projected temperature is 
[normal]increasing 
[normal]slightly faster or slower but 
[normal]similar to 
[normal]the 
[normal]general 
[normal]direction
[normal],
[normal] I get the impression most modellers would consider they were justified in their claims. But even with these three categories
[normal],
[normal] the current set of models have failed because the temperature 
[normal]is
[normal],
[normal] at present
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]approximately 
[normal]constant so they have failed 
[normal]on a 1 in 3 chance. 
[normal]14. 
[normal]The reaction by some 
[normal]scientists 
[normal]to the apparent stasis 
[normal]has been to state that the temperature of the last 20 years is higher than the previous 20 years and therefore 
[normal]climate models and assumptions are correct. 
[normal]The 
[normal]climate 
[normal]temperature has been rising for the last 
[normal]150-
[normal]300 years 
[normal]depending on whose results you look at, 
[normal]so that is hardly a surprising observation
[normal]. 
[normal] Current models are poor predictors 
[normal]and 
[normal]that creates uncertainty for 
[normal]policy 
[normal]decisions.
[normal] 
[normal]15. 
[normal]If 
[normal]climate change is primarily natural
[normal],
[normal] nothing can be done 
[normal]except to adapt. 
[normal] To describe climate change as dangerous is to downgrade our ability to create solutions and is not based on real situation
[normal]s
